		"History": "This closure was originally proposed to conserve crab resouces by reducing trawl bycatch of red king crab, tanner and snow crab.  Additional objectives included limiting potential impacts on seabirds, marine mammals, and spawning herring. The Council approved the closure in 1996 as part of a package: the Nearshore Bristol Bay Trawl Closure, the Red King Crab Savings Area, and additional steps to monitor and reduce crab bycatch. Council action: Amendment 37 to the BSAI Groundfish Fishery Management Plan.  Conservation of crab was a primary driver for this measure.  Crab stocks were in rough shape. Bristol Bay's red king crab fishery never opened during 1994 and 1995 because the population had dwindled below threshold to allow fishing. Conservation concerns also drove the constraints placed on the small \"flatfish box\" that opens April 1 to June 15, subject to a crab abundance threshold and a cap on crab bycatch. Trawling opens in this box only when managers find sufficient crab to allow targeted harvest by crabbers; if there' s no crabbing, there's no trawling either (limiting trawl bycatch and other potential impacts on crab). Trawl bycatch in this subarea is capped at 35% of the allowed king crab bycatch for the rock sole fishery.",


		
