		"History": "Closes trawling for flatfish when bycatch reaches thresholds for red king crab, bairdi Tanner crab, or halibut. The Council established Zones 1 and 2 in 1986 as part of a suite of measures to protect depressed crab stocks and halibut from trawling. Primary aim: to curtail bycatch in the new US trawl fleet delivering yellowfin sole to foreign ships. Council action: Amendment 10, BSAI Groundfish FMP. King crab had recently collapsed, and concern about trawl impacts ran  high.  The Council and NMFS judged the problem urgent enough to pass emergency regulations, which they later institutionalized with Amendment 10.  At first, the Council envisioned this package of measures—  zonal bycatch closures, bycatch caps, weekly catch reporting requirements and new authority to quickly adjust regulations  —as a provisional fix, meant to last two years while they developed a \"more comprehensive\" bycatch strategy. The rules were judged to be effective, however, and they have persisted.   The council later adjusted this bycatch trigger, scaling the cap according to abundance and biomass of red king crab— thus reducing trawl impacts when the crab population is low (see Amendment 37).",

		
