		"History": "Adopted in 1998 as part of the License Limitation Program, this closure prohibits all trawling in an area east of 140 degrees W. longitude.  Motivations included concerns over trawl preemption of local harvests, bycatch, and damage to corals.  Council action: Amendment 41 to the GOA Groundfish FMP.  The history of this closure dates to 1991, when longliners from Southeast Alaska proposed the offshore trawl ban.  Concerns centered around social impacts on local fishers, as well as damage to corals and depletion of rockfish species.  After an analysis in 1992, the Council adopted a rebuilding plan for Pacific ocean perch, Sebastes alutus, the primary rockfish species in the area.  It was not until 1998 that the Council implemented the current trawl closure.  Witherell and Woodby note that the value of this closure is \"difficult to evaluate,\" with Pacific ocean perch stock growth \"primarily attributable to large year-classes produced prior to implementation.\"  Longliners generally regard the measure as a success.",

		
