		"History": "This string of closures was initiated in 1993 to protect Steller sea lions under the Endangered Species Act.  Council action: critical habitat designation and additional protection measures.  The Alaskan population of Steller sea lions was declared threatened following a decline of around 70% from the mid-1970s to 1991. In response, NMFS defined numerous critical habitat areas in 1993, mainly in the Aleutian Islands, with attendant restrictions on fishing.  These closures - known as protection measures - have evolved over the years, with the latest revision taking effect in 2015.  Their central goal has always been to prevent fishing from depleting sea lion prey species - notably cod, pollock, and Atka mackerel - while minimizing impacts on commercial fishing efforts.  The latest revisions close 90% of AI critical habitat to Atka mackerel fishing, 22% to non-trawl cod fishing, 52% to trawl cod fishing, and 65% to pollock fishing.",

		
