		"History": "Four trawl closures around Kodiak were established in 1987 under Amendment 15 to the GOA Groundfish FMP.  Stock conservation was the primary driver for this measure. Directed fishing on Kodiak king crab had been closed since 1983, following a stock crash. \"Measures to protect concentrations of king crab, especially when they are in soft shell condition, are needed to facilitate stock rebuilding,\" stated the proposed rule. The amendment restricted bottom trawling where hgh concentrations of female red king crab were noted at Alitak, Towers and Chirikof (and to a lesser extent Barnabas). Type I areas were closed year-round; Type II areas were closed Feb 15-June 15 (considered to be a moulting period). Type III areas (sopen but subject to closure when necessary) were defined later to protect adjacent  juvenile king crab rearing or migratory areas, according to the FMP. To protect concentrations of female king crab, Amendment 26 subsequently defined \"recruitment events\" that could trigger a closure in Type III areas.  Strengthening this optional protection, Amendment 73 later established that Type III areas \"may be reclassified...as type I or Type II following a recruitment event,\" making such closures permanent.",

		
