		"History": "Federal management of the weathervane scallop fishery off Alaska began with an emergency closure of scallop fishing throughout the North Pacific EEZ in 1995.  The council took that unusual, temporary action (with support from most of the scallop fleet) to halt a single rogue vessel that sailed into Alaska and slipped outside state waters to fish unrestricted beyond three miles from shore, where no clear management authority existed yet. The vessel was defyng a state-ordered closure of the entire fishery to enforce the harvest limit.  After shutting the whole EEZ the council quickly crafted a new Fishery Management Plan for federal waters, delegating most management to the state and affirming Alaska's existing closures. Closed areas today focus mainly on control of bycatch (especially crab) and habitat impacts from scallop dredges; extensive unharvested areas also reflect a precautionary approach to harvest control for scallops, which show \"high susceptibility to local depletion and boom/bust cycles worldwide,\"  (Brawn and Scheirer 2002).  To protect fish habitat, scallop fishing is prohibited in several multi-area closures: Coral Habitat Protection Areas in the Aleutians and GOA, Aleutian Islands Habitat Conservation Areas, GOA Slope Habitat Conservation Area, Alaska Seamount Habitat Protection Areas, and Bowers Ridge Habitat Conservation Zone.",

		
